  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_1431",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Information-Theoretic 2-Round MPC without Round Collapsing: Adaptive Security, and More",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Huijia Lin",
        "email": "rachel@cs",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Tianren Liu",
        "email": "eduwee@di",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Hoeteck Wee",
        "email": "frliutr@mit",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "We present simpler and improved constructions of 2-round protocols for secure multi-party computation (MPC) in the semi-honest setting.  Our main results are new information-theoretically secure protocols for arithmetic NC1 in two settings:\n(i) the plain model tolerating up to $t < n/2$ corruptions; and\n(ii) in the OLE-correlation model tolerating any number of corruptions.\nOur protocols achieve adaptive security and require only black-box access to the underlying field, whereas previous results only achieve static security and require non-black-box field access. Moreover, both results extend to polynomial-size circuits with computational and adaptive security, while relying on black-box access to a pseudorandom generator. In the OLE correlation model, the extended protocols for circuits tolerate up to $n-1$ corruptions.\nAlong the way, we introduce a conceptually novel framework for 2-round MPC that does not rely on the round collapsing framework underlying all of the recent advances in 2-round MPC.",
    "keywords": [
      "multi-party computation"
    ],
    "category": "Cryptographic protocols",
    "publication_info": "Published by the IACR in TCC 2020",
    "last_updated": "2020-11-15",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
